-- French Stocks Gain: L'Oreal, Renault, St-Gobain, Valeo Rise, STMicro Drops
-- Alexis Xydias
-- 2010-04-23T17:12:14Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-23/french-stocks-rise-renault-l-oreal-saint-gobain-gain-as-stmicro-slides.html

          
          
             France’s CAC 40 Index added 26.65,
or 0.7 percent, to 3,951.30. The SBF 120 Index gained 0.7
percent to 2,913.85.  
 The following stocks rose or fell in the French market.
Symbols are in parentheses after company names.  
 Cie. de Saint-Gobain SA (SGO FP) rose 2.46 euros, or 6.7
percent, to 39.34 euros, the biggest jump in two months.
Europe’s biggest supplier of building materials reported first-
quarter sales of 8.74 billion euros ($11.6 billion), beating the
estimates of brokerages including Exane BNP Paribas. Wendel (MF
FP), owner of 18 percent of Saint-Gobain, advanced 2.33 euros,
or 5 percent, to 48.9.  
 Damartex SA (DAR FP) jumped 90 cents, or 4.6 percent, to
20.40 euros, taking this week’s advance to 2 percent. The maker
of thermal clothing said third-quarter revenue rose to 133.6
million euros from 128.2 million euros a year earlier.  
 L’Oreal SA (OR FP) rose 1.84 euros, or 2.3 percent, to
81.72 euros. The world’s largest cosmetics maker reported first-
quarter revenue of 4.72 billion euros, up from 4.37 billion
euros a year earlier. Sales growth accelerated to the fastest in
almost three years.  
 Renault SA (RNO FP) advanced 2.36 euros, or 6.9 percent, to
36.72 euros, the steepest gain since September. Volvo AB, the
world’s second-largest truckmaker, reported its first profit in
more than a year, beating analysts’ estimates and sending the
stock 10 percent higher in Stockholm. Renault owns 20 percent of
Volvo.  
 SES SA (SESG FP), the world’s largest publicly traded
satellite operator, dropped 78 cents, or 4.3 percent, to 17.36
euros, the worst performance since October. The company posted
first-quarter earnings that disappointed analysts and cut its
sales forecast.  
 STMicroelectronics NV (STM FP) lost 39 cents, or 5.1
percent, to 7.29 euros, the steepest decline since October.
Europe’s largest chipmaker fell after its ST-Ericsson joint
venture that produces chips for mobile phones reported a wider
first-quarter loss and forecast “approximately flat” sales.  
 Valeo SA (FR FP) rose 74 cents, or 2.8 percent, to 27.10
euros, a third gain in four days. France’s second-largest car-
parts maker had first-quarter revenue of 2.31 billion euros, up
from 1.62 billion euros a year earlier.  
